{
  "The Gibbs free energy equation is:": "",
  "G = H + TS": "",
  "G = H / TS": "",
  "G = H x TS": "",
  "G = H - TS": "",
  "The Gibbs free energy is defined as G = H - TS, where H is enthalpy, T is absolute temperature in Kelvin, and S is entropy. The change form is delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S).": "",
  "A reaction is spontaneous when delta-G is:": "",
  "Positive": "",
  "Zero": "",
  "Negative": "",
  "Equal to delta-H": "",
  "A reaction is spontaneous (thermodynamically favorable) when delta-G < 0. A negative delta-G means the process releases free energy and can proceed without external input.": "",
  "At equilibrium, what is the value of delta-G?": "",
  "Equal to zero": "",
  "Greater than zero": "",
  "Less than zero": "",
  "At equilibrium, delta-G = 0. The system has reached its lowest free energy state for the given conditions, and there is no net driving force for the reaction in either direction.": "",
  "For a reaction with delta-H < 0 and delta-S > 0, the reaction is spontaneous at:": "",
  "All temperatures": "",
  "No temperatures": "",
  "Only low temperatures": "",
  "Only high temperatures": "",
  "When delta-H is negative and delta-S is positive, delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S) is always negative because both terms contribute to making delta-G negative. The reaction is spontaneous at all temperatures.": "",
  "The standard Gibbs free energy of formation (delta-Gf) for an element in its standard state is:": "",
  "Always negative": "",
  "Always positive": "",
  "Zero by definition": "",
  "Depends on the element": "",
  "By convention, the standard Gibbs free energy of formation for any element in its most stable form at standard conditions (1 bar, usually 298 K) is defined as zero. This serves as the reference point for calculating delta-Gf of compounds.": "",
  "Which relationship connects delta-G to the equilibrium constant K?": "",
  "delta-G = RT / K": "",
  "delta-G = RT ln K": "",
  "delta-G = K / RT": "",
  "delta-G = -RT ln K": "",
  "The standard Gibbs free energy change is related to the equilibrium constant by delta-G-standard = -RT ln K, where R = 8.314 J/(mol*K) and T is the temperature in Kelvin. When K > 1, delta-G is negative (spontaneous); when K < 1, delta-G is positive.": "",
  "For a reaction with delta-H > 0 and delta-S > 0, at what condition is the reaction spontaneous?": "",
  "Never spontaneous": "",
  "At high temperatures where T(delta-S) > delta-H": "",
  "At all temperatures": "",
  "At low temperatures": "",
  "When delta-H > 0 and delta-S > 0, delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S) becomes negative only when the T(delta-S) term exceeds delta-H. This occurs at high temperatures, where the entropy contribution overcomes the endothermic enthalpy.": "",
  "What is the standard free energy change (delta-G) calculated from standard free energies of formation?": "",
  "Sum of delta-Gf(products) + Sum of delta-Gf(reactants)": "",
  "Sum of delta-Gf(products) - Sum of delta-Gf(reactants)": "",
  "Sum of delta-Gf(products) x Sum of delta-Gf(reactants)": "",
  "Sum of delta-Gf(reactants) - Sum of delta-Gf(products)": "",
  "The standard free energy change is calculated as delta-G = Sum of [n x delta-Gf(products)] - Sum of [n x delta-Gf(reactants)], where n is the stoichiometric coefficient. This is analogous to Hess's law for enthalpy.": "",
  "If K >> 1 for a reaction, what can be said about delta-G?": "",
  "delta-G is approximately zero": "",
  "delta-G is very negative": "",
  "delta-G is very positive": "",
  "delta-G cannot be determined": "",
  "Since delta-G = -RT ln K, when K >> 1, ln K is a large positive number, making delta-G a large negative number. A very negative delta-G means the reaction strongly favors product formation.": "",
  "The temperature at which a reaction changes from nonspontaneous to spontaneous can be found by setting delta-G equal to:": "",
  "One": "",
  "delta-H": "",
  "delta-S": "",
  "Setting delta-G = 0 gives delta-H - T(delta-S) = 0, so T = delta-H / delta-S. This crossover temperature is where the reaction transitions between spontaneous and nonspontaneous.": "",
  "What does the term 'Gibbs free energy' mean?": "",
  "The total energy content of a system without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "The energy required to break all bonds in a molecule in most scenarios involving energy factors": "",
  "The kinetic energy of molecules in a reaction, as conventional energy theory would suggest": "",
  "A thermodynamic quantity that combines enthalpy and entropy to predict whether a process is spontaneous at constant temperature and pressure": "",
  "Gibbs free energy (G) is a thermodynamic state function defined as G = H - TS. The change in Gibbs free energy (delta-G) determines whether a reaction is spontaneous at constant temperature and pressure. It represents the maximum amount of non-expansion work a system can perform.": "",
  "What does the term 'thermodynamically favorable' mean?": "",
  "A process that produces heat in most scenarios involving favorable factors": "",
  "A process that requires a catalyst, based on conventional assumptions about": "",
  "A process that has a negative delta-G and can occur without continuous external energy input": "",
  "A process that occurs rapidly, as conventional favorable theory would suggest": "",
  "A thermodynamically favorable process has delta-G < 0, meaning it can occur spontaneously. However, this does not mean it occurs quickly; thermodynamics tells us if a reaction CAN occur, while kinetics tells us how fast it occurs.": "",
  "What does 'standard conditions' mean when referring to delta-G-standard?": "",
  "Any conditions where the reaction is spontaneous": "",
  "Conditions at 0 degrees Celsius and 1 atm": "",
  "Conditions at equilibrium": "",
  "All reactants and products at 1 M or 1 bar, typically at 298 K": "",
  "Standard conditions for thermodynamic calculations mean all solutes at 1 M concentration, all gases at 1 bar pressure, and all pure solids and liquids in their standard states. The temperature is usually 298 K (25 degrees C) unless otherwise stated.": "",
  "What does the term 'nonspontaneous' mean for a chemical process?": "",
  "The process has delta-G > 0 and requires continuous energy input to proceed": "",
  "The process occurs slowly": "",
  "The process is impossible": "",
  "The process does not produce any products": "",
  "A nonspontaneous process has delta-G > 0, meaning it requires a continuous input of energy to proceed. It is not impossible; it simply will not occur on its own. The reverse of a nonspontaneous process is spontaneous.": "",
  "What does 'coupling reactions' mean in the context of Gibbs free energy?": "",
  "Mixing two solutions together": "",
  "Combining a nonspontaneous reaction with a spontaneous one so the overall delta-G is negative": "",
  "Running two reactions at the same temperature": "",
  "Using a catalyst to speed up a reaction": "",
  "Coupling reactions means pairing a thermodynamically unfavorable (positive delta-G) reaction with a highly favorable (negative delta-G) reaction so that the sum of their delta-G values is negative. Biological systems commonly couple ATP hydrolysis (delta-G = -30.5 kJ/mol) with endergonic processes.": "",
  "What does 'delta-G-standard' (standard free energy change) mean as distinct from delta-G?": "",
  "Delta-G-standard is the free energy change under standard conditions; delta-G is the free energy change under actual reaction conditions": "",
  "They mean the same thing, which is consistent with how delta mechanisms are understood to operate in theory": "",
  "Delta-G-standard applies only to elements, not compounds without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Delta-G-standard is always larger than delta-G in most scenarios involving delta factors": "",
  "Delta-G-standard is the free energy change when all species are in their standard states (1 M, 1 bar). Delta-G is the free energy change under actual conditions, related by delta-G = delta-G-standard + RT ln Q, where Q is the reaction quotient.": "",
  "What does the term 'free energy of formation' mean?": "",
  "The energy released when a compound dissolves": "",
  "The energy needed to break a compound into its elements": "",
  "The change in Gibbs free energy when one mole of a compound is formed from its elements in their standard states": "",
  "The total energy stored in a compound": "",
  "The standard free energy of formation (delta-Gf) is the change in Gibbs free energy when one mole of a compound is formed from its constituent elements, each in their standard states. It is a reference value used to calculate delta-G for reactions.": "",
  "What does the term 'reaction quotient' (Q) mean in the delta-G equation?": "",
  "The same as the equilibrium constant K": "",
  "The ratio of product concentrations to reactant concentrations at any point during a reaction, raised to their stoichiometric powers": "",
  "The number of moles of products divided by moles of reactants": "",
  "The rate of the forward reaction divided by the rate of the reverse": "",
  "The reaction quotient Q has the same mathematical form as the equilibrium constant K, but uses the actual concentrations at any given moment, not just at equilibrium. In the equation delta-G = delta-G-standard + RT ln Q, Q determines how far the system is from equilibrium.": "",
  "What does the term 'exergonic' mean?": "",
  "A reaction that occurs at high temperature": "",
  "A reaction that requires free energy": "",
  "A reaction that releases free energy (delta-G < 0)": "",
  "A reaction that releases heat": "",
  "Exergonic means the reaction releases free energy (delta-G < 0). This is distinct from exothermic (releases heat, delta-H < 0). An exergonic reaction is spontaneous, while an endergonic reaction (delta-G > 0) is nonspontaneous.": "",
  "What does the term 'endergonic' mean?": "",
  "A reaction that occurs at all temperatures": "",
  "A reaction that releases free energy": "",
  "A reaction that absorbs heat": "",
  "A reaction that absorbs free energy (delta-G > 0)": "",
  "Endergonic means the reaction requires an input of free energy (delta-G > 0). Such reactions are nonspontaneous and will not proceed without a continuous supply of energy. In biological systems, endergonic reactions are often driven by coupling with ATP hydrolysis.": "",
  "A chemist determines that a reaction has delta-H = -120 kJ/mol and delta-S = -200 J/(mol*K). At what temperature does this reaction become nonspontaneous?": "",
  "The reaction is always spontaneous": "",
  "1200 K": "",
  "600 K": "",
  "300 K": "",
  "Setting delta-G = 0: 0 = delta-H - T(delta-S). T = delta-H/delta-S = -120,000 J / (-200 J/K) = 600 K. Below 600 K, delta-G < 0 (spontaneous). Above 600 K, the large negative entropy term dominates, making delta-G > 0 (nonspontaneous).": "",
  "An industrial chemist calculates delta-G-standard for the synthesis of ammonia: N2(g) + 3H2(g) -> 2NH3(g), delta-H = -92.4 kJ and delta-S = -198.3 J/K at 298 K. What is delta-G-standard?": "",
  "-92.4 kJ": "",
  "-33.3 kJ": "",
  "-151.5 kJ": "",
  "+33.3 kJ": "",
  "delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S) = -92,400 J - (298 K)(-198.3 J/K) = -92,400 + 59,093 = -33,307 J = -33.3 kJ. The reaction is spontaneous at 298 K, but the negative entropy means it becomes nonspontaneous at higher temperatures.": "",
  "A researcher finds that delta-G-standard = -5.7 kJ/mol for a reaction at 298 K. What is the equilibrium constant K? (R = 8.314 J/(mol*K))": "",
  "1.0": "",
  "0.10": "",
  "10": "",
  "100": "",
  "Using delta-G-standard = -RT ln K: -5700 = -(8.314)(298) ln K. ln K = 5700/2478 = 2.30. K = e^2.30 = 10.0. A moderately negative delta-G corresponds to K = 10, meaning products are moderately favored.": "",
  "A biologist studying cellular metabolism knows that the hydrolysis of ATP has delta-G-standard = -30.5 kJ/mol. She wants to couple it with a reaction that has delta-G-standard = +18.0 kJ/mol. What is the overall delta-G-standard?": "",
  "-12.5 kJ/mol": "",
  "+12.5 kJ/mol": "",
  "+48.5 kJ/mol": "",
  "-48.5 kJ/mol": "",
  "When reactions are coupled, their delta-G values are additive: delta-G(overall) = -30.5 + 18.0 = -12.5 kJ/mol. The overall reaction is spontaneous because the ATP hydrolysis provides more than enough free energy to drive the endergonic reaction.": "",
  "A geochemist studying the decomposition of limestone (CaCO3 -> CaO + CO2) finds delta-H = +178.3 kJ and delta-S = +160.5 J/K. Above what temperature is this reaction spontaneous?": "",
  "298 K (25 degrees C)": "",
  "1111 K (838 degrees C)": "",
  "500 K (227 degrees C)": "",
  "835 K (562 degrees C)": "",
  "T = delta-H/delta-S = 178,300 J / 160.5 J/K = 1111 K (838 degrees C). Above 1111 K, the T(delta-S) term exceeds delta-H, making delta-G negative. This is why lime kilns must operate at very high temperatures to decompose limestone.": "",
  "A student calculates delta-G for a reaction at 298 K and finds delta-G-standard = +10.0 kJ/mol. If the actual concentrations give Q = 0.001, what is delta-G? (R = 8.314 J/(mol*K))": "",
  "+27.1 kJ/mol": "",
  "0 kJ/mol": "",
  "+10.0 kJ/mol": "",
  "-7.1 kJ/mol": "",
  "delta-G = delta-G-standard + RT ln Q = 10,000 + (8.314)(298) ln(0.001) = 10,000 + (2478)(-6.908) = 10,000 - 17,114 = -7,114 J = -7.1 kJ/mol. Even though delta-G-standard is positive, the very low Q (mostly reactants present) makes the reaction spontaneous in the forward direction.": "",
  "An engineer is evaluating the combustion of methane: CH4(g) + 2O2(g) -> CO2(g) + 2H2O(l). Using standard free energies of formation: delta-Gf(CO2) = -394.4 kJ/mol, delta-Gf(H2O) = -237.1 kJ/mol, delta-Gf(CH4) = -50.7 kJ/mol, delta-Gf(O2) = 0. What is delta-G-standard?": "",
  "-817.9 kJ": "",
  "-818.9 kJ": "",
  "-444.4 kJ": "",
  "-631.5 kJ": "",
  "delta-G = [(-394.4) + 2(-237.1)] - [(-50.7) + 2(0)] = [-394.4 - 474.2] - [-50.7] = -868.6 + 50.7 = -817.9 kJ. The large negative value confirms that methane combustion is highly spontaneous under standard conditions.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical researcher needs to know whether the dissolution of a drug (delta-H = +25 kJ/mol, delta-S = +100 J/(mol*K)) is spontaneous at body temperature (37 degrees C = 310 K). What is delta-G?": "",
  "+25.0 kJ/mol": "",
  "-31.0 kJ/mol": "",
  "-6.0 kJ/mol": "",
  "+6.0 kJ/mol": "",
  "delta-G = delta-H - T(delta-S) = 25,000 - (310)(100) = 25,000 - 31,000 = -6,000 J = -6.0 kJ/mol. The dissolution is spontaneous at body temperature because the entropy increase at 310 K is large enough to overcome the endothermic enthalpy.": "",
  "A student measures K = 2.5 x 10^-3 for a reaction at 298 K. What is delta-G-standard? (R = 8.314 J/(mol*K))": "",
  "+14.8 kJ/mol": "",
  "-14.8 kJ/mol": "",
  "-5.9 kJ/mol": "",
  "+5.9 kJ/mol": "",
  "delta-G-standard = -RT ln K = -(8.314)(298) ln(2.5 x 10^-3) = -(2478)(-5.991) = +14,846 J = +14.8 kJ/mol. Since K < 1, delta-G-standard is positive, indicating that reactants are favored at equilibrium under standard conditions.": "",
  "A materials scientist is studying the rusting of iron: 4Fe(s) + 3O2(g) -> 2Fe2O3(s). Given delta-G-standard = -1484 kJ at 298 K, she wants to know why iron still requires time to rust despite the highly negative delta-G. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "The reaction is actually not spontaneous": "",
  "Delta-G only predicts thermodynamic favorability, not reaction rate; the rusting has a high activation energy": "",
  "Solid-state reactions always have positive delta-G": "",
  "The equilibrium constant must be less than 1": "",
  "Thermodynamics (delta-G) tells us whether a reaction CAN occur, while kinetics tells us how FAST it occurs. Rusting has a very negative delta-G (thermodynamically very favorable) but a significant activation energy barrier, which makes it a slow process at room temperature. This distinction between thermodynamics and kinetics is fundamental.": ""
}